{"author":{"id":"1260ec7e1e5fa2a41651bb0f92ca6302285a1546d07f404ff26b865b47ab5c24"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1726254455,"nonce":"YLnWc8/VYB1F9kA2yeNLrYV+Z+o=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDODBZtRc6MEYpY","github-url":"https://github.com/dandi/dandi-cli/issues/1455#issuecomment-2349959768"},"message":"Just to dismiss some confusion, @kabilar you are running \n```\n!export DANDI_API_KEY=\u003cdandi_api_key\u003e\n!dandi download https://api.dandiarchive.org/api/assets/9a4b64df-433c-4efe-a1e7-2ae55b3f95ac/download/\n```\nin two different cells?  then I guess sessions are not shared etc, so effect of `export` would be lost for the next command. \nTry smth like\n\n```\n!DANDI_API_KEY=\u003cdandi_api_key\u003e dandi download https://api.dandiarchive.org/api/assets/9a4b64df-433c-4efe-a1e7-2ae55b3f95ac/download/\n```\n\nalternatively, you could just set it in env within that ipython notebook:\n\n```python\nimport os\nos.environ['DANDI_API_KEY'] = \"yourkey\"\n```\n\nbefore you `import dandi` etc so it could be picked up by that process and its children (may be... ;))\n\nSimilarly the `export` you do in a child subshell in `3.` has no effect on the state of python process there.  If within ipython notebook and just to do it interactively, can simply do how we do it in https://github.com/dandi/example-notebooks/blob/master/dandi/archive_stats.ipynb\n\n```python\nclient = DandiAPIClient()\nclient.dandi_authenticate()\n```\nwhich should prompt you for key if it is unknown.","files":null},{"type":3,"timestamp":1747677968,"nonce":"27BMHlWAuv85jF6TZQPwZVosAsg=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDODBZtRc6sXj0f","github-url":"https://github.com/dandi/dandi-cli/issues/1455#issuecomment-2891857183"},"message":"there we no activity on this for awhile.  If issue remains, please feel welcome to reopen","files":null},{"type":4,"timestamp":1747677969,"nonce":"4cBANGVF1P61aAhDbv/VlYT/VrA=","metadata":{"github-id":"CE_lADODBZtRc6Nr70OzwAAAAQgMHgR"},"status":2}]}